<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-03T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-03T21:00:00-05:00" n="798" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d798">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/2062: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-04T11:00:00+09:00">June 4, 1940—11
                                    a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 2 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>404. Department’s 218, May 18, 4 p.m., and Shanghai’s 410, May 12, 1
                                p.m., terrorist activities. My British colleague<note n="82" xml:id="d798fn82">Sir Robert L. Craigie British Ambassador in
                                    Japan.</note> has informed me that he is now prepared to make
                                representations to the Foreign Office. I propose to make an oral and
                                informal approach to the Foreign Office as suitable occasion offers
                                within the next few days urging the advisability of doing away with
                                unlawful armed groups in areas under Japanese control at
                                Shanghai.</p>
                            <p>Shanghai please repeat to Chungking and Peiping.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>